# Predict the probability of a term deposit
df$predicted_prob <- predict(glm_model, type = "response")

# Create a confusion matrix

# Predict using the GLM model
df$predicted <- ifelse(predict(glm_model, type = "response") >= 0.5, 1, 0)
# Calculate the confusion matrix and classification report
confusion_matrix <- table(df$deposit, df$predicted)
accuracy <- sum(diag(confusion_matrix)) / sum(confusion_matrix)
classification_report <- data.frame(
  Precision = confusion_matrix[2, 2] / sum(confusion_matrix[, 2]),
  Recall = confusion_matrix[2, 2] / sum(confusion_matrix[2, ]),
  F1_Score = 2 * (confusion_matrix[2, 2] / sum(confusion_matrix[, 2])) * (confusion_matrix[2, 2] / sum(confusion_matrix[2, ]))
)

## In conclusion, we performed exploratory data analysis (EDA) on the bank marketing dataset to understand the patterns and relationships between the various features and the target variable. We found that several features, such as age, balance, and duration, were strongly correlated with the target variable, indicating their importance in predicting whether a client will subscribe to a term deposit.

## We also conducted inferential statistical analysis to test hypotheses and explore the significance of various features on the target variable. We found that several features, such as age, job type, education level, and marital status, were significant predictors of the target variable.
